  "prompt": "Where can I find a training data set (free or not) for patent/prior art search to train a deep learning engine to select relevant prior art/ patents?",
  "response": "Finding training datasets for patent or prior art searches can be challenging, but there are several sources you can explore. Here are some suggestions:\n\n1. **USPTO (United States Patent and Trademark Office)**: The USPTO offers bulk data downloads, including patent applications, granted patents, and other related information. You can use these datasets for training purposes. Visit the USPTO Bulk Data website: [USPTO Bulk Data](https://www.uspto.gov/products/bulk-data-products).\n\n2. **EPO (European Patent Office)**: The EPO provides access to patents through its Espacenet service. While it does not offer bulk downloads for free, you can query and retrieve individual patent documents. Explore Espacenet: [Espacenet](https://www.epo.org/searching-for-patents/technical/espacenet.html).\n\n3. **Google Patents**: Google provides a searchable database of patents from various countries. You can access patent data, including full texts and citations, which can be useful for creating a training dataset. Visit Google Patents: [Google Patents](https://patents.google.com/).\n\n4. **Lens.org**: Lens.org is a free patent and scholarly search platform that provides access to millions of patent documents. You can use their API to retrieve patent data in bulk. Explore Lens.org: [Lens.org](https://www.lens.org/).\n\n5. **Public Domain Patent Data**: Websites like FreePatentsOnline.com offer free access to patent documents. While bulk downloads might not be available, you can manually query and gather data: [FreePatentsOnline](http://www.freepatentsonline.com/).\n\n6. **Commercial Providers**: Companies such as LexisNexis PatentSight, Clarivate, and others provide comprehensive patent datasets, often with advanced features tailored to specific needs. These services are typically paid, but they offer high-quality, curated data.\n\n7. **University Collaborations**: Some research institutions and universities may have ongoing projects on patent data analysis and could collaborate with you or provide access to datasets. Consider reaching out to relevant academic departments.\n\n8. **Open Source Projects**: Occasionally, open-source projects related to patent analysis might share datasets for research purposes. Platforms like GitHub or Zenodo could be good places to look for such projects.\n\nBefore proceeding with any dataset, make sure to verify the licensing and usage terms to ensure compliance with legal restrictions.",
